Title:
VX-API

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- VX-API is a Visual Studio solution containing a large collection of Windows-focused “malicious functionality” building blocks intended to accelerate malware and offensive PoC development.  
- It aggregates many small, reusable implementations across areas like anti-debugging, evasion, process creation, process injection, shellcode execution, and helper utilities (PE/TEB/PEB access, hashing-based API resolution, string/memory routines).  
- The repo emphasizes low-level Windows internals techniques (TEB/PEB parsing, ntdll usage, custom GetProcAddress via hashing) and includes offensive tradecraft such as AMSI bypass patterns, sleep obfuscation, PEB masquerading, and multiple injection/execution primitives.  
- It also includes components relevant to credential access workflows (LSASS PID discovery helpers) and a set of “process injection testing applications” to validate techniques.  
- Useful primarily for malware developers, red teamers, and security researchers who want reference implementations and a modular codebase to prototype or study offensive techniques.  
- Interesting because it consolidates many commonly reimplemented primitives (with attribution) into one navigable solution, making comparative experimentation and rapid PoC assembly easier.

Technical Focus:
- Windows internals (TEB/PEB, ntdll, loader structures)  
- API hashing and dynamic function resolution (custom GetProcAddress variants)  
- Evasion techniques (AMSI bypass patterns, sleep obfuscation, PEB masquerading, unhooking/restoration)  
- Process injection & execution primitives (APC/AtomBombing, WPM+CRT, process reflection, threadpool-based execution)  
- Alternate process creation methods (COM/UAC/INF/protocol handlers/NtCreateUserProcess)  
- Cryptography/compression utilities (hashing, MD5, CAB/ZIP extraction, XPRESS/LZ helpers)

Use Cases:
- Build and test process injection and shellcode execution PoCs on Windows
- Prototype evasion features (anti-debug checks, AMSI bypass patterns, sleep obfuscation)
- Implement hashed API resolution and PEB/TEB-based environment discovery
- Explore alternate process creation vectors and COM-based execution paths
- Create internal red team tooling modules (selectively reusing specific functions)

